demy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury&nbsp;</em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects!&nbsp;</strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy&nbsp;</strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns!</strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats&nbsp;</em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals!</strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts&nbsp;</strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;6h 12m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-23-making-a-mock-up-fancy-silhouette-skirt/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-23-making-a-mock-up-fancy-silhouette-skirt/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-07T20:00:41+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-07T20:00:41+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 23. Making a Mock-Up Fancy Silhouette Skirt."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 23. Making a Mock-Up Fancy Silhouette Skirt."><meta itemprop="description" content="I have put the mock-up on the dress-form, placed the dress-form on the spinning tray, and put a soft mat underneath it."><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Practical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. practical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 23. Making a Mock-Up Fancy Silhouette Skirt.</h1><p><strong>I have put the mock-up on the dress-form, placed the dress-form on the spinning tray, and put a soft mat underneath it. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image002.jpg" alt="goldub-399"></p><p><strong>Right now, we should examine the skirt very carefully and decide what cutting / sewing lines we need to add.</strong> Just take a pencil or a marker and start drawing new princess seam lines and other cutting lines as seen in the picture of the garment.</p><p><strong>Why is it easier to do it on a half-scale mock-up? First of all, </strong>it is easier because you have all garment proportions before your eyes. If you are working with full-size mock-up and dress-form, you will have to keep walking a considerable distance away from it to see whether all is looking good. The half-scale dress-form allows you to evaluate the results of your work from a close distance.</p><p><strong>And this is exactly what I will be doing now. </strong>I will look at the picture and transfer all major designer lines on the mock-up. If you are making your own design, you can go creative now without looking at any pictures.</p><p><strong>Why did I put a soft mat under the spinning tray? </strong>It will be very convenient to spread apart and pin down separate parts of the mock-up while working on the flare and, particularly, on the train.</p><p><strong>I cut in half the side back piece (3) following the princess seam line up to the marked level. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image004.jpg" alt="goldub-400"></p><p><strong>After cutting the piece, I determine the best amount of flare and pin the separated parts down to the soft mat. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image006.jpg" alt="goldub-401"></strong></p><p><strong>After pinning down the strips, we can take all measurements of the resulting gore, cut it from the mock-up fabric, and insert it in place. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image008.jpg" alt="goldub-402"></p><p><strong>I do the same with the side front and side back pieces: cut them up, spread the divided parts apart by the required width, and pin them down to the floor. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image010.jpg" alt="goldub-403"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image012.jpg" alt="goldub-404"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image014.jpg" alt="goldub-405"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image016.jpg" alt="goldub-406"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image018.jpg" alt="goldub-407"></p><p><strong>This preliminary work allows you to estimate </strong>whether there are enough strips and whether they are lying beautifully and the fabric is arranged nicely. It also helps you decide how long to make the train. You can see how the skirt expands in different areas and you don’t have to make guesses: it is all before your eyes.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image020.jpg" alt="goldub-408"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image022.jpg" alt="goldub-409"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image024.jpg" alt="goldub-410"></p><p><strong>I guess now you can see </strong>that I made the gores longer to be able to pin them to the mat this way.</p><p><strong>There are some more handy tips which will help you in working with the mock-up. </strong></p><p><strong>How to put the mock-up on the dress-form? </strong></p><p><strong>There are many theories: </strong>some dressmakers put it on seam allowances out, others prefer keeping them on the inside. Generally speaking, it depends on the type of skirt you are making. It also depends on the thickness of your mock-up fabric: if it is rather thin, like mine, then you can safely keep the seam allowances on the inside because they will not create excess thickness.</p><p><strong>You should obviously put the mock-up on the dress-form seam allowances out if you need to use them in further adjustments. For example, </strong>if you doubt the precision of your calculations, then exposed seam allowances will allow you to take in or let out some fabric in relevant areas.</p><p><strong>By the way, you must never make bar tacks when sewing mock-up seams! And here is why: </strong></p><p><strong>- Firstly,</strong> bar tacks are stiff and solid and they may tear delicate mock-up fabric;</p><p><strong>- Secondly,</strong> bar tacks will make it hard to apply further adjustments. It won’t be easy, for example, to adjust the length of the gore with bar tacks made along the joining seams. Just treat the mock-up with due care and you won’t have to worry about seams coming undone.</p><p><strong>So I have marked new lines on my mock-up skirt in accordance with the picture. </strong>Here is the result:</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image026.jpg" alt="goldub-411"></p><p><strong>Let us talk about these lines in more detail. </strong></p><p><strong>Here is how the princess seams will go. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image028.jpg" alt="goldub-412"></strong></p><p><strong>The vertical princess seams will be shifted like that: </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image030.jpg" alt="goldub-413"></strong></p><p><strong>Here is the side insert:</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image032.jpg" alt="goldub-414"></strong></p><p><strong>The princess seam of the side back gore which was cut in half will go at a light incline toward the side insert and not as a straight line. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image034.jpg" alt="goldub-415"></strong></p><p><strong>The princess seam of the side front gore will also be inclined. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image036.jpg" alt="goldub-416"></strong></p><p><strong>Here is the rounded part of the side insert. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image038.jpg" alt="goldub-417"></strong></p><p><strong>The separately cut central part of the skirt: </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image040.jpg" alt="goldub-418"></strong></p><p><strong>And another princess seam:</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image042.jpg" alt="goldub-419"></strong></p><p><strong>The top edge and the seam allowances of the central back seam were marked correctly. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image044.jpg" alt="goldub-420"></strong></p><p><strong>Here is the centre of the front: </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image046.jpg" alt="goldub-421"></strong></p><p><strong>In addition, I have moved the front princess seam line closer to the side. </strong></p><p><strong>The initial skirt pattern looked like this. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image048.jpg" alt="goldub-422"></p><p><strong>I have cut up the initial centre piece following the guideline which marks the direction of lengthwise grain. </strong>Please note that I have cut it up at a light incline toward the centre and joined the cut-off part with the side front piece.</p><p><strong>Consequently, the position of the front princess seam has changed. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image050.jpg" alt="goldub-423"></p><p><strong>I have also moved the beginning of the flare (point A) a little higher up the new princess seam line (point A1).</strong></p><p>The flare initially began at the same level along the front princess seam line (point A), the side seam line (point B), and the back princess seam line (point C).</p><p>I have decided to make the flare line gradually go up from point C, through the new point B1 marked along the side seam line, and to the new point A1 marked along the new front princess seam line.</p><p><strong>As the result, there is a triangular flare line at the front. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image052.jpg" alt="goldub-424"></strong></p><p><strong>We have achieved the desired intermediate result, </strong>i.e. marked all main princess seam lines on the mock-up.</p><p><strong>I highly recommend you make notches or mark transverse lines along all lines for aligning the pieces before working with lace inserts. </strong>The more notches or marks you make, the easier further work will be.</p><p>You won’t have to think over how to align the cut-out pieces with such control marks there.</p><p><strong>What is also important, </strong>we have just re-drawn all princess seam lines on non-woven fusible webbing, i.e. basically on paper. When you start sewing with actual fabric, the pieces will inevitably start to stretch out.</p><p><strong>And in that case, notches or transverse lines marked along the alignment lines will be of great help! </strong></p><p><strong>If your fabric pieces stretch out, </strong>you will align them referring to these control marks. And then there will be no distortion when you sew them together.</p><p><strong>That is why you should remember to make control marks along new princess seam lines and cutting lines. </strong>When you transfer these marks on the adjusted pattern, you will know for sure where and how the pieces are supposed to be aligned.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image054.jpg" alt="goldub-425"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image056.jpg" alt="goldub-426"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image058.jpg" alt="goldub-427"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image060.jpg" alt="goldub-428"></p><p><strong>Now, I suggest we focus on the bottom part of the skirt before taking the mock-up off the dress-form for further work. </strong></p><p><strong>I want these straight strips to stop above floor level and transform into triangles down the bottom. </strong></p><p>We will insert lace gores between the triangles. And the lace gores will reach down to the floor.</p><p>Looking at the original picture, I can only see main fabric reaching down to the floor in the middle of the front. All other gores made of the main fabric are shaped as triangles, which makes the skirt look a lot more elegant.</p><p>You should also understand that we are only working on one half of our mock-up skirt now, drawing right on it. It is impossible to draw absolutely symmetric lines on the other half of the skirt.</p><p><strong>I draw triangular gores starting from the front vertical midline (red lines). </strong>And I draw cutting lines going from the vertex of each triangle down to the bottom of the strip (red dashed line).</p><p><strong>I draw the vertex of the triangle a little lower on each subsequent gore starting from the side front piece and finishing with the central back piece or the train. </strong>This will make the skirt look more beautiful and artistic.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image062.jpg" alt="goldub-429"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image064.jpg" alt="goldub-430"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image066.jpg" alt="goldub-431"></p><p><strong>This is how the vertex points will be positioned as compared to floor level. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image068.jpg" alt="goldub-432"></strong></p><p>We need to cut the mock-up in pieces to continue working on the pattern. <strong>I number all parts of the skirt to avoid confusion and know for sure where this or that piece should go. </strong></p><p><strong>First of all, I number all sides of the triangular gores (red numbers). </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image070.jpg" alt="goldub-433"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image072.jpg" alt="goldub-434"></p><p><strong>I need to number the sides of all gores because I will measure their lengths and the distance between them before taking the mock-up off the dress-form. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image074.jpg" alt="goldub-435"></p><p><strong>These measurements will be used to calculate the dimensions of lace inserts which will be sewn in between the gores. </strong></p><p>I will draw schematic triangular gores on a piece of paper and write it down that, for example, side 3 is this many centimeters, side 4 is that many centimeters, and the distance between them is such or such. And I will do so for the whole bottom of the skirt.</p><p><strong>So when I cut the mock-up in smaller parts, I will be able to construct triangular lace inserts following these measurements. </strong></p><p>Then, I will align the lace inserts with the parted gore pieces to get one whole piece of a very precise configuration.</p><p><strong>I have another useful tip for you. </strong></p><p><strong>If you feel like you might get confused after cutting up the skirt, then I recommend you should number all parts of the skirt and not just the gores (see the blue numbers in the picture below). </strong></p><p><strong>I numbered the initial pieces in the very beginning of work, too (black numbers). </strong></p><p><strong>With all parts numbered, you will assemble the skirt again easier after cutting it up.</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image076.jpg" alt="goldub-436"></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image078.jpg" alt="goldub-437"></strong></p><p><strong>I highly recommend you should take pictures of your mock-up from all sides after numbering its parts. </strong></p><p>This will help you restore the full picture and avoid confusion.</p><p><strong>And now let us talk about the train.</strong></p><p><strong>What concerns its length, </strong>it all depends on your client’s preferences and on the style of the skirt.</p><p><strong>You can lengthen the rectangular parts of the back with strips of fabric before taking measurements for the gores so you can imagine what the train will look like.</strong></p><p>In any case, you will need to polish up the shape of the train on the finished mock-up or on the actual skirt to make it beautiful. And you will need to adjust the skirt length along the front and the sides.</p><p><strong>It is also compulsory to adjust the shape of the bottom edge regardless of whether you will use a petticoat or not. </strong></p><p><strong>I have lengthened the back strips, taken all gore measurements, sketched them on a piece of paper, and marked down the lengths of all sides of the triangles. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image080.jpg" alt="goldub-438"></strong></p><p><strong>Triangle with sides 1 and 2. </strong></p><p>Each side (1 and 2) is 35cm long and the flare is 11cm.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image082.jpg" alt="goldub-439"></p><p><strong>Triangle with sides 3 and 4.</strong></p><p>Each side (3 and 4) is 33.5cm long and the flare is 11cm like in the previous case.</p><p><strong>Triangle with sides 5 and 6. </strong>Strip 6 was lengthened.</p><p>Side 5 is 32cm long and side 6 − 36cm long. There is 12cm between the strips of fabric.</p><p><strong>We are moving to the back of the skirt where all strips were lengthened. </strong>Keep an image of the train in your head.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image084.jpg" alt="goldub-440"></p><p><strong>Triangle with sides 7 and 8. </strong></p><p>Side 7 is 40cm long, side 8 is 45cm long, and there is 10.5cm between them. Please note that the train gores will, as a rule, have different amounts of flare. It is necessary to achieve a beautiful shape.</p><p><strong>Triangle with sides 9 and 10. </strong></p><p>Side 9 is 52cm long, side 10 is 61cm long, and there is as much as 26cm between them, a rather big flare.</p><p><strong>We have approached the central part of the back. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2023.files/image086.jpg" alt="goldub-441"></strong></p><p><strong>Since the central part of the back is divided in half, both sides of the central gore are the same. </strong></p><p>The sides of the triangle are 63cm each and there is 14cm between them.</p><p>When I start making the pattern, I will fold the mock-up in half along the back vertical midline. As the result, the central gore will be folded right in half. One half of the gore will have a flare of 7cm.</p><p>I will give the final shape to the bottom edge of the central gore when the skirt is finished.</p><p>But in any case, when you lengthen those strips, you should provide for some excess so you can polish up the shape of the train later.</p><p><strong>We have done everything we should with the mock-up! </strong></p><p>Now we can safely take it off the dress-form and examine it on a flat surface to make all princess seam lines smoother and more graceful, especially where they arrive at the side seams.</p><p><strong>There is one more important moment. </strong>Make sure you can see the direction of lengthwise grain on all pieces, even the smallest ones, after cutting the mock-up in parts. We will refer to these lines very often during further work.</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank"